**03-03-26 — Setting Up the Monitors**

**Phase Overview**
* Now that Ubuntu, Apache, pfSense, and Hyper-V are all set up and working, I began the second phase of development: setting up the Windows Attacker Client and the SIEM.

**SIEM Virtual Machine Setup**
* First, I segmented the SIEM from the Ubuntu VM. Doing this ensures that if Ubuntu goes down, the SIEM will not go down as well.
* The new VM is called **Ubuntu-Splunk-SIEM**.
* Configuration:
  * 4 GB memory
  * 60 GB storage (dedicated for logs)
* One thing I did differently this time was **disable Dynamic Memory** and assign the storage statically.
* After installing Ubuntu the same way as the previous VM, I created a different login specifically for the SIEM environment:
  * Username: `siemlogin`

**Network Configuration**
* Since I had previously messed up an installation, I verified connectivity first.
* I obtained the IP address of the Ubuntu Splunk server and **pinged it from pfSense** to confirm the network connection.
* I then changed the VM’s IP address to **10.0.0.20** using **pfSense DHCP Static Mapping** based on the VM’s MAC address.
* Before doing this, I adjusted the DHCP range to:
  * **10.0.0.10 – 10.0.0.19**
* The IP address change was successful.

**System Preparation**

* After verifying Ubuntu was fully updated, I installed required utilities:
  * `wget`
  * `curl`
  * `gnupg`

**Installing Splunk**

* Installing Splunk ended up being simpler than I originally expected.
* Instead of downloading manually, I used a shortened `wget` command.
Original command example:
wget -O splunk-10.2.1-c892b66d163d-linux-amd64.deb "https://download.splunk.com/products/splunk/releases/10.2.1/linux/splunk-10.2.1-c892b66d163d-linux-amd64.deb"

Simplified command used:
wget -O splunk.deb "https://download.splunk.com/products/splunk/releases/10.2.1/linux/splunk-10.2.1-c892b66d163d-linux-amd64.deb"

Installation steps:
sudo dpkg -i splunk.deb

Start Splunk:
sudo /opt/splunk/bin/splunk start --accept-license --answer-yes --no-prompt --run-as-root

Enable auto-start:
sudo /opt/splunk/bin/splunk enable boot-start --accept-license

Verify status:
sudo /opt/splunk/bin/splunk status

Access Splunk web interface:
http://10.0.0.20:8000

**Creating a Dedicated Splunk User**
To properly run Splunk under its own user account:
Create the user:
sudo useradd -m splunk

Assign ownership:
sudo chown -R splunk:splunk /opt/splunk

Switch to the Splunk user:
sudo su - splunk

Start Splunk again under this account:
/opt/splunk/bin/splunk start --accept-license

This time a prompt appeared, allowing me to create the **Splunk admin account**.
After that I was able to log into the Splunk platform normally.

**Configuring Splunk Log Receiving**
Inside the Splunk interface:
* Navigated to **Settings**
* Created a **new receiving port: 9997**

Verify Splunk is listening:
sudo ss -tulnp | grep 9997
This confirmed Splunk is ready to receive logs.

**Installing the Splunk Universal Forwarder**
Download the forwarder:
wget -O splunkforwarder.deb "https://download.splunk.com/products/universalforwarder/releases/10.2.1/linux/splunkforwarder-10.2.1-c892b66d163d-linux-amd64.deb"

I created another login:
* `forwarderlogin`
When starting the forwarder, I encountered an issue with the `splunkd` instance and had to terminate it before continuing.

Start the forwarder:
sudo /opt/splunkforwarder/bin/splunk start --accept-license

Configure the forwarder to send logs to the SIEM:
sudo /opt/splunkforwarder/bin/splunk add forward-server 10.0.0.20:9997
I initially forgot to restart Splunk, so I restarted it and continued configuring monitoring inputs.

**Log Monitoring Configuration**
System log monitoring:
sudo /opt/splunkforwarder/bin/splunk add monitor /var/log/syslog

Authentication log monitoring:
sudo /opt/splunkforwarder/bin/splunk add monitor /var/log/auth.log

After restarting both services, the forwarder successfully connected.
Verification showed:
* **1 active forwarder**
* **Port 9997 operational**
* Logs successfully reaching Splunk

(Screenshots were captured for documentation.)

**RAM Constraint Issue**
Due to my system having only **16 GB of RAM**, I had to reconsider my VM allocation.
Originally planned:
* Separate Windows attacker VM

Adjustment made:
* SIEM kept the same
* Ubuntu internal server reduced to **1 GB RAM**
* pfSense firewall VM reduced to **1 GB RAM**
* Temporarly used **Command Prompt** over a whole Windows VM

This frees enough resources to continue expanding the lab later.
